data.content:
## .NET 8 Migration: BackgroundProcessor

### Critical Breaking Changes

1. **`Thread.Abort()` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException`** in .NET Core+. It's completely removed.
2. **`Thread.ResetAbort()` also throws.** The entire `ThreadAbortException` pattern is dead.
3. **`volatile bool` for signaling** works but `CancellationToken` is the modern, cooperative pattern — it can unblock waiting calls.

### Migrated Code

```csharp
public class BackgroundProcessor : IDisposable
{
    private Task? _workerTask;
    private CancellationTokenSource? _cts;

    public void Start()
    {
        _cts = new CancellationTokenSource();
        _workerTask = Task.Run(() => ProcessLoop(_cts.Token));
    }

    private async Task ProcessLoop(CancellationToken token)
    {
        while (!token.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            try
            {
                // Pass the token so blocking calls can be interrupted
                var item = await GetNextItemAsync(token);
                await ProcessItemAsync(item, token);
            }
            catch (OperationCanceledException) when (token.IsCancellationRequested)
            {
                // Graceful shutdown requested — replaces ThreadAbortException
                RollbackCurrentTransaction();
                break; // exit loop cleanly; finally still runs
            }
            finally
            {
                FlushBuffers();
            }
        }
    }

    public async Task StopAsync(TimeSpan? timeout = null)
    {
        if (_cts is null || _workerTask is null)
            return;

        _cts.Cancel(); // signals the token — unblocks awaiting calls

        // Wait for graceful shutdown with a timeout
        var effectiveTimeout = timeout ?? TimeSpan.FromSeconds(5);
        if (await Task.WhenAny(_workerTask, Task.Delay(effectiveTimeout)) != _workerTask)
        {
            // Worker didn't finish in time — log a warning.
            // There is NO equivalent to Abort(). You must design
            // all downstream calls to respect CancellationToken.
        }
    }

    public void Dispose()
    {
        _cts?.Cancel();
        _workerTask?.GetAwaiter().GetResult(); // sync wait if not already stopped
        _cts?.Dispose();
    }
}
```

### Key Pitfalls

| Pitfall | Detail |
|---|---|
| **No force-kill exists** | `Thread.Abort()` has no replacement. If `GetNextItem()` blocks on a non-cancellable call (raw socket, P/Invoke), you **cannot** interrupt it. You must refactor those calls to accept `CancellationToken`. |
| **`OperationCanceledException` ≠ `ThreadAbortException`** | `ThreadAbortException` auto-rethrew at the end of each `catch`. `OperationCanceledException` is a normal exception — if you catch it, it stays caught. No `ResetAbort()` needed. |
| **`volatile bool` can't unblock** | The old `_running = false` can't wake a thread stuck in a blocking `GetNextItem()`. `CancellationToken` can, if the callee supports it — this is why the token is passed through. |
| **`Thread.Sleep` → `Task.Delay`** | `Thread.Sleep` blocks a thread pool thread. Use `await Task.Delay(duration, token)` instead. |
| **Fire-and-forget `Task.Run`** | Unobserved exceptions crash silently. Always `await _workerTask` in `StopAsync`/`Dispose` to surface errors. |
| **`IHostedService` alternative** | In ASP.NET Core / Generic Host apps, prefer `BackgroundService` which handles the lifecycle for you and integrates with the host's shutdown token. |

### If You Can't Make Blocking Calls Cancellable

As a last resort for truly non-cancellable legacy code:

```csharp
// Wrapper to abandon (not abort) a stuck call
var completedTask = await Task.WhenAny(
    Task.Run(() => LegacyBlockingCall()),  // may never return
    Task.Delay(timeout, token)
);
if (completedTask != _workerTask)
    Log.Warn("Abandoned stuck call — thread leaked");
```

This **leaks the thread** — it's not killed, just orphaned. Acceptable only as a transitional step while you refactor the blocking call.
